The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Metro Briefs

 A renovated Alipore Special jail will be unveiled next month. Women convicts from Presidency jail, Dum Dum Central jail and Howrah jail will be shifted to the special jail, said an officer on Sunday. The jail had earlier accommodated more than 70 non-criminal lunatics, who have been shifted to various homes run by the state health department in the city and elsewhere in the state.

 Two youths allegedly stole cash and jewellery worth Rs 40,000 from a house in Sonagachi, in north Calcutta, early on Sunday. The tenant of the house has lodged a police complaint. No one has been arrested.

 A fire broke out at a godown stacked with cotton on JN Mukherjee Road in Malipanchghara, Howrah, on Sunday morning. Police said the fire was detected around 11.30 am. Four tenders took an hour to douse the blaze. No one was injured. The cause of the fire is yet to be ascertained.

 The Garia bridge was opened on Saturday by irrigation minister Subhas Naskar. It took nearly 18 months to complete the bridge at a cost of Rs 70 lakh. It could not be opened last month, as some autorickshaws used to be parked there, said an official.

 Police on Sunday organised a legal awareness camp in Barasat, on the citys northern fringes, for the underprivileged who are often harassed for their ignorance of law. Sub-divisional officer of Barasat S.M.H. Meerza and magistrates of the district court were among those present at the camp. 




